#. type: Title ==
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4498
#, no-wrap
msgid "Specifying the Working Directory"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4502
msgid ""
"Each port is extracted into a working directory, which must be writable. The "
"ports system defaults to having `DISTFILES` unpack in to a directory called `"
"${DISTNAME}`. In other words, if the [.filename]#Makefile# has:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4512
msgid ""
"....  PORTNAME=\tfoo DISTVERSION=\t1.0 ....  then the port's distribution "
"files contain a top-level directory, [.filename]#foo-1.0#, and the rest of "
"the files are located under that directory.  A number of variables can be "
"overridden if that is not the case."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4513
#, no-wrap
msgid "`WRKSRC`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4517
msgid ""
"The variable lists the name of the directory that is created when the "
"application's distfiles are extracted. If our previous example extracted "
"into a directory called [.filename]#foo# (and not [.filename]#foo-1.0#) "
"write:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4524
msgid "....  WRKSRC=\t${WRKDIR}/foo ....  or possibly"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4529
msgid "....  WRKSRC=\t${WRKDIR}/${PORTNAME} ...."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4530
#, no-wrap
msgid "`WRKSRC_SUBDIR`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4534
msgid ""
"If the source files needed for the port are in a subdirectory of the "
"extracted distribution file, set `WRKSRC_SUBDIR` to that directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4539
msgid "....  WRKSRC_SUBDIR=\tsrc ...."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4540
#, no-wrap
msgid "`NO_WRKSUBDIR`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4544
msgid ""
"If the port does not extract in to a subdirectory at all, then set "
"`NO_WRKSUBDIR` to indicate that."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4549
msgid "....  NO_WRKSUBDIR=\tyes ...."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4552
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Because `WRKDIR` is the only directory that is supposed to be writable during the build, and is used to store many files recording the status of the build, the port's extraction will be forced into a subdirectory.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4555
#, no-wrap
msgid "Conflict Handling"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4559
msgid ""
"There are three different variables to register a conflict between packages "
"and ports: `CONFLICTS`, `CONFLICTS_INSTALL` and `CONFLICTS_BUILD`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4562
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The conflict variables automatically set the variable `IGNORE`, which is more fully documented in <<dads-noinstall,Marking a Port Not Installable with `BROKEN`, `FORBIDDEN`, or `IGNORE`>>.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4566
msgid ""
"When removing one of several conflicting ports, it is advisable to retain "
"`CONFLICTS` in those other ports for a few months to cater for users who "
"only update once in a while."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4570
msgid ""
"If the package cannot coexist with other packages (because of file "
"conflicts, runtime incompatibilities, etc.). `CONFLICTS_INSTALL` check is "
"done after the build stage and prior to the install stage."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4574
msgid ""
"If the port cannot be built when other specific ports are already installed. "
"Build conflicts are not recorded in the resulting package."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4580
msgid ""
"If the port cannot be built if a certain port is already installed and the "
"resulting package cannot coexist with the other package. `CONFLICTS` check "
"is done prior to the build stage and prior to the install stage.  The most "
"common content of one of these variable is the package base of another port. "
"The package base is the package name without the appended version, it can be "
"obtained by running `make -V PKGBASE`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4581
#, no-wrap
msgid "Basic usage of `CONFLICTS*`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4587
msgid ""
"package:dns/bind99[] cannot be installed if package:dns/bind910[] is present "
"because they install same files. First gather the package base to use:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4597
msgid ""
"....  % make -C dns/bind99 -V PKGBASE bind99 % make -C dns/bind910 -V "
"PKGBASE bind910 ....  Then add to the [.filename]#Makefile# of package:dns/"
"bind99[]:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4604
msgid ""
"....  CONFLICTS_INSTALL=\tbind910 ....  And add to the [.filename]#Makefile# "
"of package:dns/bind910[]:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4609
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"CONFLICTS_INSTALL=\tbind99\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4613
msgid ""
"Sometimes, only certain versions of another port are incompatible.  When "
"this is the case, use the full package name including the version.  If "
"necessary, use shell globs like `*` and `?` so that all necessary versions "
"are matched."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4614
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `CONFLICTS*` With Globs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4622
msgid ""
"From versions from 2.0 and up-to 2.4.1_2, package:deskutils/gnotime[] used "
"to install a bundled version of package:databases/qof[].  To reflect this "
"past, the [.filename]#Makefile# of package:databases/qof[] contains:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4632
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"CONFLICTS_INSTALL=\tgnotime-2.[0-3]* \\\n"
"\t\t\tgnotime-2.4.0* gnotime-2.4.1 \\\n"
"\t\t\tgnotime-2.4.1_[12]\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"The first entry match versions `2.0` through `2.3`, the second all the revisions of `2.4.0`, the third the exact `2.4.1` version, and the last the first and second revisions of the `2.4.1` version.\n"
"\n"
"package:deskutils/gnotime[] does not have any conflicts line because its current version does not conflict with anything else.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4636
msgid ""
"The variable `DISABLE_CONFLICTS` may be temporarily set when making targets "
"that are not affected by conflicts.  The variable is not to be set in port "
"Makefiles."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4641
msgid "....  % make -DDISABLE_CONFLICTS patch ...."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4642
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing Files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4647
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `install` phase is very important to the end user because it adds files to their system. All the additional commands run in the port [.filename]#Makefile#'s `*-install` targets should be echoed to the screen. _Do not_ silence these commands with `@` or `.SILENT`.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4650
#, no-wrap
msgid "`INSTALL_*` Macros"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4654
msgid ""
"Use the macros provided in [.filename]#bsd.port.mk# to ensure correct modes "
"of files in the port's `*-install` targets. Set ownership directly in [."
"filename]#pkg-plist# with the corresponding entries, such as `@(_owner_,"
"_group_,)`, `@owner _owner_`, and `@group _group_`. These operators work "
"until overridden, or until the end of [.filename]#pkg-plist#, so remember to "
"reset them after they are no longer needed. The default ownership is `root:"
"wheel`. See <<plist-keywords-base,Base Keywords>> for more information."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4655
msgid "`INSTALL_PROGRAM` is a command to install binary executables."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4656
msgid "`INSTALL_SCRIPT` is a command to install executable scripts."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4657
msgid ""
"`INSTALL_LIB` is a command to install shared libraries (but not static "
"libraries)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4658
msgid ""
"`INSTALL_KLD` is a command to install kernel loadable modules. Some "
"architectures do not like having the modules stripped, so use this command "
"instead of `INSTALL_PROGRAM`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4659
msgid ""
"`INSTALL_DATA` is a command to install sharable data, including static "
"libraries."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4663
msgid ""
"`INSTALL_MAN` is a command to install manpages and other documentation (it "
"does not compress anything).  These variables are set to the man:install[1] "
"command with the appropriate flags for each situation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4666
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Do not use `INSTALL_LIB` to install static libraries, because stripping them renders them useless. Use `INSTALL_DATA` instead.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4669
#, no-wrap
msgid "Stripping Binaries and Shared Libraries"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4675
msgid ""
"Installed binaries should be stripped. Do not strip binaries manually unless "
"absolutely required. The `INSTALL_PROGRAM` macro installs and strips a "
"binary at the same time. The `INSTALL_LIB` macro does the same thing to "
"shared libraries.  When a file must be stripped, but neither "
"`INSTALL_PROGRAM` nor `INSTALL_LIB` macros are desirable, `${STRIP_CMD}` "
"strips the program or shared library. This is typically done within the "
"`post-install` target. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4683
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"post-install:\n"
"\t${STRIP_CMD} ${STAGEDIR}${PREFIX}/bin/xdl\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"When multiple files need to be stripped:\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4686
msgid "....  post-install:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4686
#, no-wrap
msgid "for l in geometry media body track world"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4688
#, no-wrap
msgid "\t${STRIP_CMD} ${STAGEDIR}${PREFIX}/lib/lib${PORTNAME}-${l}.so.0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4688
#, no-wrap
msgid "endfor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4693
msgid ""
"....  Use man:file[1] on a file to determine if it has been stripped. "
"Binaries are reported by man:file[1] as `stripped`, or `not stripped`. "
"Additionally, man:strip[1] will detect programs that have already been "
"stripped and exit cleanly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4700
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When `WITH_DEBUG` is defined, elf files _must not_ be stripped.\n"
"\n"
"The variables (`STRIP_CMD`, `INSTALL_PROGRAM`, `INSTALL_LIB`, ...) and <<uses,`USES`>> provided by the framework handle this automatically.\n"
"\n"
"Some software, add `-s` to their `LDFLAGS`, in this case, either remove `-s` if `WITH_DEBUG` is set, or remove it unconditionally and use `STRIP_CMD` in `post-install`.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4703
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing a Whole Tree of Files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4709
msgid ""
"Sometimes, a large number of files must be installed while preserving their "
"hierarchical organization. For example, copying over a whole directory tree "
"from `WRKSRC` to a target directory under `PREFIX`. Note that `PREFIX`, "
"`EXAMPLESDIR`, `DATADIR`, and other path variables must always be prepended "
"with `STAGEDIR` to respect staging (see <<staging,Staging>>).  Two macros "
"exist for this situation. The advantage of using these macros instead of "
"`cp` is that they guarantee proper file ownership and permissions on target "
"files. The first macro, `COPYTREE_BIN`, will set all the installed files to "
"be executable, thus being suitable for installing into [.filename]#PREFIX/"
"bin#. The second macro, `COPYTREE_SHARE`, does not set executable "
"permissions on files, and is therefore suitable for installing files under [."
"filename]#PREFIX/share# target."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4718
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"post-install:\n"
"\t${MKDIR} ${STAGEDIR}${EXAMPLESDIR}\n"
"\t(cd ${WRKSRC}/examples && ${COPYTREE_SHARE} . ${STAGEDIR}${EXAMPLESDIR})\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"This example will install the contents of the [.filename]#examples# directory in the vendor distfile to the proper examples location of the port.\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4729
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"post-install:\n"
"\t${MKDIR} ${STAGEDIR}${DATADIR}/summer\n"
"\t(cd ${WRKSRC}/temperatures && ${COPYTREE_SHARE} \"June July August\" ${STAGEDIR}${DATADIR}/summer)\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"And this example will install the data of summer months to the [.filename]#summer# subdirectory of a [.filename]#DATADIR#.\n"
"\n"
"Additional `find` arguments can be passed via the third argument to `COPYTREE_*` macros. For example, to install all files from the first example except Makefiles, one can use these commands.\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4739
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"post-install:\n"
"\t${MKDIR} ${STAGEDIR}${EXAMPLESDIR}\n"
"\t(cd ${WRKSRC}/examples && \\\n"
"\t${COPYTREE_SHARE} . ${STAGEDIR}${EXAMPLESDIR} \"! -name Makefile\")\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"These macros do not add the installed files to [.filename]#pkg-plist#. They must be added manually. For optional documentation (`PORTDOCS`, see <<install-documentation>>) and examples (`PORTEXAMPLES`), the `%%PORTDOCS%%` or `%%PORTEXAMPLES%%` prefixes must be prepended in [.filename]#pkg-plist#.\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4740
#, no-wrap
msgid "Install Additional Documentation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4748
msgid ""
"If the software has some documentation other than the standard man and info "
"pages that is useful for the user, install it under `DOCSDIR` This can be "
"done, like the previous item, in the `post-install` target.  Create a new "
"directory for the port. The directory name is `DOCSDIR`. This usually equals "
"`PORTNAME`. However, if the user might want different versions of the port "
"to be installed at the same time, the whole `PKGNAME` can be used.  Since "
"only the files listed in [.filename]#pkg-plist# are installed, it is safe to "
"always install documentation to `STAGEDIR` (see <<staging,Staging>>). Hence "
"`.if` blocks are only needed when the installed files are large enough to "
"cause significant I/O overhead."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4759
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"post-install:\n"
"\t${MKDIR} ${STAGEDIR}${DOCSDIR}\n"
"\t${INSTALL_MAN} ${WRKSRC}/docs/xvdocs.ps ${STAGEDIR}${DOCSDIR}\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"On the other hand, if there is a DOCS option in the port, install the documentation in a `post-install-DOCS-on` target. These targets are described in <<options-targets>>.\n"
"\n"
"Here are some handy variables and how they are expanded by default when used in the [.filename]#Makefile#:\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4760
#, no-wrap
msgid "`DATADIR` gets expanded to [.filename]#PREFIX/shared/PORTNAME#.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4761
#, no-wrap
msgid "`DATADIR_REL` gets expanded to [.filename]#share/PORTNAME#.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4762
#, no-wrap
msgid "`DOCSDIR` gets expanded to [.filename]#PREFIX/shared/doc/PORTNAME#.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4763
#, no-wrap
msgid "`DOCSDIR_REL` gets expanded to [.filename]#share/doc/PORTNAME#.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4764
#, no-wrap
msgid "`EXAMPLESDIR` gets expanded to [.filename]#PREFIX/shared/examples/PORTNAME#.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4766
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"`EXAMPLESDIR_REL` gets expanded to [.filename]#share/examples/PORTNAME#.\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4769
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `DOCS` option only controls additional documentation installed in `DOCSDIR`. It does not apply to standard man pages and info pages. Things installed in `EXAMPLESDIR` are controlled by the `EXAMPLES` option.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4775
msgid ""
"These variables are exported to `PLIST_SUB`. Their values will appear there "
"as pathnames relative to [.filename]#PREFIX# if possible. That is, [."
"filename]#share/doc/PORTNAME# will be substituted for `%%DOCSDIR%%` in the "
"packing list by default, and so on. (See more on [.filename]#pkg-plist# "
"substitution <<plist-sub,here>>.)  All conditionally installed documentation "
"files and directories are included in [.filename]#pkg-plist# with the `%"
"%PORTDOCS%%` prefix, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4783
msgid ""
"....  %%PORTDOCS%%%%DOCSDIR%%/AUTHORS %%PORTDOCS%%%%DOCSDIR%%/CONTACT ....  "
"As an alternative to enumerating the documentation files in [.filename]#pkg-"
"plist#, a port can set the variable `PORTDOCS` to a list of file names and "
"shell glob patterns to add to the final packing list. The names will be "
"relative to `DOCSDIR`. Therefore, a port that utilizes `PORTDOCS`, and uses "
"a non-default location for its documentation, must set `DOCSDIR` "
"accordingly. If a directory is listed in `PORTDOCS` or matched by a glob "
"pattern from this variable, the entire subtree of contained files and "
"directories will be registered in the final packing list. If the `DOCS` "
"option has been unset then files and directories listed in `PORTDOCS` would "
"not be installed or added to port packing list. Installing the documentation "
"at `PORTDOCS` as shown above remains up to the port itself. A typical "
"example of utilizing `PORTDOCS`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4788
msgid "....  PORTDOCS=\tREADME.* ChangeLog docs/* ...."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4793
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The equivalents of `PORTDOCS` for files installed under `DATADIR` and `EXAMPLESDIR` are `PORTDATA` and `PORTEXAMPLES`, respectively.\n"
"\n"
"The contents of [.filename]#pkg-message# are displayed upon installation. See <<porting-message,the section on using [.filename]#pkg-message#>> for details. [.filename]#pkg-message# does not need to be added to [.filename]#pkg-plist#.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4796
#, no-wrap
msgid "Subdirectories Under `PREFIX`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4800
msgid ""
"Try to let the port put things in the right subdirectories of `PREFIX`. Some "
"ports lump everything and put it in the subdirectory with the port's name, "
"which is incorrect. Also, many ports put everything except binaries, header "
"files and manual pages in a subdirectory of [.filename]#lib#, which does not "
"work well with the BSD paradigm. Many of the files must be moved to one of "
"these directories: [.filename]#etc# (setup/configuration files), [."
"filename]#libexec# (executables started internally), [.filename]#sbin# "
"(executables for superusers/managers), [.filename]#info# (documentation for "
"info browser) or [.filename]#share# (architecture independent files). See "
"man:hier[7] for details; the rules governing [.filename]#/usr# pretty much "
"apply to [.filename]#/usr/local# too. The exception are ports dealing with "
"USENET \"news\". They may use [.filename]#PREFIX/news# as a destination for "
"their files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4801
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use `BINARY_ALIAS` to Rename Commands Instead of Patching the Build"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4807
msgid ""
"When `BINARY_ALIAS` is defined it will create symlinks of the given commands "
"in a directory which will be prepended to `PATH`.  Use it to substitute "
"hardcoded commands the build phase relies on without having to patch any "
"build files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4808
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `BINARY_ALIAS` to Make `gsed` Available as `sed`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4816
msgid ""
"Some ports expect `sed` to behave like GNU sed and use features that man:"
"sed[1] does not provide. GNU sed is available from package:textproc/gsed[] "
"on FreeBSD.  Use `BINARY_ALIAS` to substitute `sed` with `gsed` for the "
"duration of the build:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4823
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"BUILD_DEPENDS=\tgsed:textproc/gsed\n"
"...\n"
"BINARY_ALIAS=\tsed=gsed\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4826
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `BINARY_ALIAS` to Provide Aliases for Hardcoded `python3` Commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4832
msgid ""
"A port that has a hardcoded reference to `python3` in its build scripts will "
"need to have it available in `PATH` at build time. Use `BINARY_ALIAS` to "
"create an alias that points to the right Python 3 binary:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4840
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"....\n"
"USES=\tpython:3.4+,build\n"
"...\n"
"BINARY_ALIAS=\tpython3=${PYTHON_CMD}\n"
"....\n"
"\n"
"See <<using-python,Using Python>> for more information about `USES=python`.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: documentation/content/en/books/porters-handbook/makefiles/chapter.adoc:4845
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Binary aliases are created after the dependencies provided via `BUILD_DEPENDS` and `LIB_DEPENDS` are processed and before the `configure` target. This leads to various limitations. For example, programs installed via `TEST_DEPENDS` cannot be used to create a binary alias as test dependencies specified this way are processed after binary aliases are created.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""
